Emote System
============

To begin with, all emotes are handled through the emote daemon, EMOTE_D,
which handles all of the visibility checks, parsing, room messaging, etc.
Any emote consists of two basic parts, the 'RULE' and the 'Message String'.

The RULE is a sequence of 0 or more tokens representing variable arguments
passed to the emote. Valid tokens for a RULE are 'LIV', 'OBJ', and 'STR'.
Any arguments given with the emote, will be compared to the known RULEs for
that emote, and if a match is found, the corresponding Message String will
be used.

  ex. (Emote: wave  RULE: LIV) will match if a player types 'wave bozo'
      and Bozo is a living object the player has access too.

The Message String is the text that is displayed with the emote, with
variables in place for the words that change depending upon who is seeing
the message. Note that if the variables do not match the rules, the emote
may be buggy. Where applicable a variable can be modified by a number
indicating who/what is the first person of referred to by the variable,
followed by a modifying argument. Targets are numbered by the order they
are specified in, in the rule,  with the emoter being living target 0.
Capitalizing the variable will capitalize the output. Valid variables are:

                 $n ...living target - defaults to $n0s.
                       Arguments are: b: objective [you, him]
                                      g: nominative [you, Bob]
                                      o: reflexive [yourself, himself]
                                      s: subjective [you, he]
                                      p: name [Bob, Bob]
                       The b, o and s forms always revert to the g form
                       when a target appears for the first time in the
                       message.
                 $p ...possessive [your, his].
                       first target appearance is named [your, Bob's].
                 $r ...reflexive [yourself, himself].
                 $t ...same as $n but default is $t1o.
                 $o ...object for OBJ rule or string for STR rule.
                 $v ...verb forms.
                       Argument is the verb to be conjugated.

             To make different messages for every viewer, concatenate
             output strings with '&&' in the form:
                <emoter msg>&&<room msg>&&<target 1 msg>&&<target 2 msg>...

  ex. (Emote: wave  RULE: LIV  Msg: "$N $vwave at $t.") will give the
      message "You wave at Bozo." to you, "Clown waves at you." to Bozo,
      and "Clown waves at Bozo." to everyone else in the room if you were
      to use the emote 'wave bozo'.


All emotes are added to EMOTE_D through the command 'addemote'. This
information is also available in 'help addemote'.



Variable Emotes
===============

Some emotes return variable text depending on certain factors beyond the
score of EMOTE_D to check. In order for this to work, a small command must
be coded that tells EMOTE_D what message should be used. Any Variable Emote
will be in the special emote directory, '/cmds/soul/'.

The main function in this command will be:

  string get_emote(string sArg, object *aoWho) { }

inside of which the emote Message String will be constructed. 'sArg' will
be the matching RULE used by the player, and 'aoWho' is the array of
objects involved in the emote. The return string value is the Message
String EMOTE_D should use to construct the emote messages.

  ex. (From our wave emote, LIV rule example above.)

/cmds/soul/wave.c

string get_emote(string sArg, object *aoWho) {
  if (sArg != "LIV") return "";			// We only want LIV rules

  if (random(2))
    return "$N $vwave in crisp military fashion at $t.";
  else
    return "$N $vwave parade-style at $t.";
}

   This will return the first Message String 50% of the time, and the
   second Message String the other 50% of the time.


The last thing needed for a variable emote to work is to link the small
emote command you made in /cmds/soul/ to EMOTE_D itself. To do this you
would still use the 'addemote' command to add the emote 'wave', for RULE
LIV, but instead of giving a Message String, you would re-direct it to
your emote command with '->wave'. This will cause EMOTE_D to go to the
emote command for the Message String when the emote 'wave' is called with
the matching 'LIV' RULE.



Guild Emotes
============

Guild emotes are definitions stored in a separate, guild-scoped mapping in
EMOTE_D. They use the same RULE and Message String grammar as global emotes,
but only active members of the selected guild can list, preview, invoke, or
use them through a channel soul.

Create a static guild emote with the normal addemote flow and the -guild
option:

  addemote -guild Street_Samurai jackin STR
  New message: $N $vjack into $o.

The guild name is matched case-insensitively against GUILD_NAMES. Definitions
are persisted in /secure/savedir/soul with the rest of the emote daemon state.
Because that save data is environment-local, definitions must still be added
or migrated separately wherever they are expected to exist.

Use these commands to inspect and remove guild definitions:

  showemote -guild Street_Samurai jackin
  rmemote -guild Street_Samurai jackin STR
  rmemote -guild Street_Samurai jackin

Omitting -guild operates on a global emote. A new guild-emote name may not
collide with a global emote, another guild's emote, or a command available to
the architect creating it.

A guild emote only needs an object under /cmds/soul/ when its output must be
computed dynamically. Put the get_emote() object in the lower-case guild
directory, then use a guild redirect as the stored Message String:

  /cmds/soul/psionicist/spoon.c
  ->Guild_Psionicist_spoon

The guild token in a redirect must use the configured guild name. Static
guild emotes should store their Message String directly and do not need a
redirect object.

Players can discover and inspect the definitions available to them with:

  feelings guild [<guild>] [<prefix>]
  semote <emote>
  emoteapropos guild [<guild>] <text>

See also: help guild emotes, help addemote, help showemote, help rmemote




